abstract: >
  kinn is a real-time Bayesian diagnostic interview engine. After every
  stakeholder answer, it computes the Expected Information Gain of every
  candidate next question against a Bayesian belief over the stakeholder's
  situation, and asks the one that collapses the most uncertainty. The frame
  is BED-LLM (Bayesian Experimental Design with LLM samplers): Claude Opus
  4.7 is both the answer-distribution sampler and the belief updater. DSPy
  with GEPA compiles the prompts offline; runtime is a forced-tool-call loop
  with prompt caching, two-phase recompile, and dual-algedonic state. Built
  solo as a hackathon submission (kinn → kinn2 → kinn3 iterations) within the
  Apr 21–28, 2026 window.
